definition.value: This is a rodent-specific behavior. Whisker trimming and barbering are either normal or abnormal depending on the mouse strain. Barbering is particularly common in C57BL/6 and A2G but nearly unseen in other strains. This term should always be used in relation to the control and strain should be specified.

definition.value: The pilomotor reflex occurs in many mammals; for example, porcupines raise their quills when threatened. Piloerection as a response to cold or fear is vestigial in humans; as humans retain only very little body hair, the reflex (in humans) now provides no known benefit.
